{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f95fdb7-e235-4311-909d-6cfa1b88a9f1","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events** API in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- Each handler receives the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call native APIs directly if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"504c9a1f-2529-4491-b086-d365a7b03e09","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"DBCD:852E1:97E73:BF1E6:69F54AB3"},"id":"c4172279-687e-4396-943f-c0be1de5455a","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:52:10.113Z","parentId":"2919c973-3425-4140-a108-d6f6e7c2d4cd"}
